definition.value: A porphyrin compound substituted with one or more bromine atoms bonded to a methine group of the porphyrin ring.
A porphyrin compound which is substituted via the pyrrole groups in the porphyrin ring.
A porphyrin compound which is substituted via the methine groups in the porphyrin ring.
A substituted porphyrin compound containing one or more groups of formula BRR' (where R or R' can be H).
A borylporphyrin compound containing two groups of formula BRR' (where R or R' can be H).
A borylporphyrin compound containing one group only of formula BRR' (where R or R' can be H).
A substituted porphyrin compound containing one or more groups of formula BRR' (where R or R' can be H) bonded to one or more methine groups of the porphyrin ring.
A substituted porphyrin compound containing one or more groups of formula BRR' (where R or R' can be H) bonded to a pyrrole group of the porphyrin ring.
A substituted porphyrin compound containing four groups of formula BRR' (where R or R' can be H).
A biological role played by the molecular entity or part thereof within a biochemical context.
A role played by the molecular entity or part thereof which causes the development of a pathological process.
A biological role which describes how a drug interacts within a biological system and how the interactions affect its medicinal properties.
A compound containing two porphyrin rings.
A compound consisting of a porphyrin ring bonded via one of its pyrrole groups to a pyrrole group on a second porphyrin ring.
Any molecule or ion capable of binding to a central metal atom to form coordination complexes.
A  chemical role played by the molecular entity or part thereof in a photochemical process.
A role played by a molecular entity or part thereof in a photobiochemical process.
Any substance introduced into a living organism with therapeutic or diagnostic purpose.
An organosulfur compound with the general formula R-N=C=S.
The (R)-enantiomer of homocitric acid.
The 8S-epimer of cedrol.
The stable isotope of tin with relative atomic mass 118.903311, 8.59 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin (1)/2.
The stable isotope of tin with relative atomic mass 119.902199 and 32.58 atom percent natural abundance.
